{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"82c28398-e3ce-40b7-884c-e857e105293c","content":"Use conditional compilation with `#if` directives in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\nEach implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (which is already target-filtered in the default `.csproj`). This ensures only the relevant platform code compiles for each target, so it won't break on any platform.\n\n**Alternative (no `#if`):** Use partial classes or the `Platforms/` folder convention with a shared registration helper that each platform folder provides — but the `#if` approach above is the most common and straightforward.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"409aece2-f7cc-4a1e-a0cf-9dd80fe2c751","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` in a .NET MAUI app's `MauiProgram.cs` file. This is a common pattern in MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase since this is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI dependency injection.","outputTokens":375,"requestId":"9425:3F33F0:13EF668:1668DEF:6A067339"},"id":"c0816d0e-47a9-4362-8b54-b6d17039608d","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:13:38.881Z","parentId":"7703f1e6-e683-47bf-b500-0113d8729d23"}
